<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FF69FC08FDEB458B" blockId="11.[229,669,922,975]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
<heading id="D0CF81E3A224FFF2FF69FC08FDEB458B" centered="true" fontSize="8" level="2" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" reason="8">
ECOLOGY OF 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FEF1FC08FE4745EA" box="[381,466,922,943]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FEF1FC08FE4745EA" box="[381,466,922,943]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">ANOLIS</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ASSEMBLAGES OF NORTHWESTERN SOUTH AMERICA
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FF01FC72FEE7401E" blockId="11.[141,757,992,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
Several studies have revealed relationships amongst morphology, ecology, and behaviour (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FDBCFC6DFF504277" author="Miles DB &amp; Ricklefs RE" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="1629 - 1640" refId="ref11529" refString="Miles DB, Ricklefs RE. 1984. The correlation between ecology and morphology in deciduous forest passerine birds. Ecology 65: 1629 - 1640." type="journal article" year="1984">Miles &amp; Ricklefs, 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FF5DFB8CFEFD4270" author="Pianka ER" box="[209,360,1054,1076]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="325 - 336" refId="ref11773" refString="Pianka ER. 1986. Ecological phenomena in evolutionary perspective. In: Polunin N, ed. Ecosystem theory and application. Chichester, New York: Wiley and Sons Ltd, 325 - 336." type="book chapter" year="1986">Pianka, 1986</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FE10FB8CFE774277" box="[412,482,1054,1075]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FE10FB8CFE774277" box="[412,482,1054,1075]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, some morphological attributes translate into performance capability, and these capabilities constrain the ecology of anoles (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FD27FBC9FF4442D4" author="Losos JB" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="69 - 388" refId="ref11189" refString="Losos JB. 1990 a. Ecomorphology, performance capability, and scaling of West Indian Anolis lizards: an evolutionary analysis. Ecological Monographs 60: 69 - 388." type="journal article" year="1990">Losos, 1990a</bibRefCitation>
). Anole lizards are an example of ecomorphological relationships. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FEB8FB0AFE7942EA" author="Williams EE" box="[308,492,1176,1198]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="47 - 89" refId="ref12346" refString="Williams EE. 1972. The origin of faunas. Evolution of lizard congeners in a complex island fauna: a trial analysis. Evolutionary Biology 6: 47 - 89." type="journal article" year="1972">Williams (1972)</bibRefCitation>
coined ecomorph as a term to define groups of anole species with similar morphology and habitat use but without close phylogenetic relationships. Later, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FEE7FB66FE6D434D" author="Losos JB" box="[363,504,1268,1289]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="69 - 388" refId="ref11189" refString="Losos JB. 1990 a. Ecomorphology, performance capability, and scaling of West Indian Anolis lizards: an evolutionary analysis. Ecological Monographs 60: 69 - 388." type="journal article" year="1990">Losos (1990a</bibRefCitation>
, c) demonstrated quantitatively the links amongst morphological, ecological, and behavioural traits in Greater Antilles anoles. Owing to the evolution of subdigital lamellae, anoles are mostly arboreal but several species also show diverse microhabitat uses, and are semiarboreal, terrestrial, or semiaquatic (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FECCFA39FE534385" author="Losos JB" box="[320,454,1451,1473]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" refId="ref11304" refString="Losos JB. 2009. Lizards in an evolutionary tree: ecology and adaptive radiation of anoles. Berkeley: University of California Press." type="book" year="2009">Losos, 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Colombian anoles are not an exception and also use a wide variety of microhabitats; six morphotypes are arboreal, and the remaining four are semi-arboreal. Semiaquatic species also occur but they cannot be classified into a particular morphotype.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FF2AF9F1FE2140B7" blockId="11.[141,757,992,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Although the ecology of many mainland anole species is unknown, the matches between morphotypes and ecomorphs found here permit us to infer some associations between our morphological groups and their predominant habitat use.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FF2AF96EFB074449" blockId="11.[141,757,992,1902]" lastBlockId="11.[803,1419,197,1901]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
Giant species of MT10 and some of MT7 use mostly tree trunks in the upper strata and canopy. 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FD27F888FF7D410A" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1899" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="frenatus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FD27F888FF7D410A" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis frenatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FEACF8ABFE4F410B" authorityName="Daudin" authorityYear="1802" box="[288,474,1849,1871]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FEACF8ABFE4F410B" box="[288,474,1849,1871]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seem ecologically similar to the crown-giant ecomorph from the Greater Antil- les (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FCDCFF57FBBD469F" author="Irschick DJ &amp; Vitt LJ &amp; Zani P &amp; Losos JB" box="[848,1064,197,219]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="2191 - 2203" refId="ref10995" refString="Irschick DJ, Vitt LJ, Zani P, Losos JB. 1997. A comparison of evolutionary radiations in mainland and West Indian Anolis lizards. Ecology 78: 2191 - 2203." type="journal article" year="1997">
Irschick 
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FC23FF57FC49469E" box="[943,988,197,218]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">et al</emphasis>
., 1997
</bibRefCitation>
), but 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FBEAFF57FB65469E" authorityName="Daudin" authorityYear="1802" box="[1126,1264,197,218]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FBEAFF57FBE2469E" box="[1126,1143,197,218]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FB08FF57FB65469E" box="[1156,1264,197,218]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not enough large to be a giant anole and it also matches with the trunk-crown ecomorph. The absence of MT 
<quantity id="4CC09B6AA224FFF2FAC7FE90FA1F475C" box="[1355,1418,258,280]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" unit="in" value="10.0">10 in</quantity>
<collectingRegion id="49FCF86DA224FFF2FCAFFEB3FC0C4772" box="[803,921,289,310]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
can be explained because giant anole evolution was constrained by the presence of larger canopy lizards, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FC6DFECCFBC94737" authority="plica" box="[993,1116,350,371]" class="Reptilia" family="Tropiduridae" genus="Plica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="plica">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FC6DFECCFBC94737" box="[993,1116,350,371]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Plica plica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FB14FECCFA164737" baseAuthorityName="Guichenot" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[1176,1411,350,371]" class="Reptilia" family="Tropiduridae" genus="Uracentron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flaviceps">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FB14FECCFA164737" box="[1176,1411,350,371]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Uracentron flaviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which are large lizards that use trunks of large trees (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FCA7FE09FBE447F4" author="Vitt LJ &amp; Zani PA &amp; Avila-Pires TCS" box="[811,1137,411,433]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="1876 - 1882" refId="ref12289" refString="Vitt LJ, Zani PA, Avila-Pires TCS. 1997. Ecology of the arboreal tropidurid lizard Tropidurus (= Plica) umbra in the Amazon region. Canadian Journal of Zoology 75: 1876 - 1882." type="journal article" year="1997">Vitt, Zani &amp; Avila-Pires, 1997</bibRefCitation>
; R. A. Moreno-Arias pers. observ. 2014). These lizards may have restricted the evolution of anoles towards giant forms owing to niche incumbency or a priority effect.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FCB0FD84FB5F4546" blockId="11.[803,1419,197,1901]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
In addition, several species of MT8 use shrubs or tree trunks and branches in the canopy and understorey strata, but species of MT6 are more common in the understorey to herbaceous strata. These two morphotypes apparently do not have a Caribbean ecomorph counterpart, although 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FB19FD3CFACC4487" authorityName="Oeser" authorityYear="1933" box="[1173,1369,686,707]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="biporcatus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FB19FD3CFACC4487" box="[1173,1369,686,707]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis biporcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FCAFFD5FFC6644A6" box="[803,1011,717,738]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chocorum">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FCAFFD5FFC6644A6" box="[803,1011,717,738]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis chocorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are recognized as crown-giants (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FCA7FD7EFBB04545" author="Castro-Herrera F" box="[811,1061,748,769]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" refId="ref10633" refString="Castro-Herrera F. 1988. Niche structure of an anole community in a tropical rain forest within the Choco region of Colombia. Unpublished DPhil Thesis, North Texas State University." type="book" year="1988">Castro-Herrera, 1988</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FBBFFD7EFB2A4546" author="Losos JB" box="[1075,1215,748,770]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" refId="ref11304" refString="Losos JB. 2009. Lizards in an evolutionary tree: ecology and adaptive radiation of anoles. Berkeley: University of California Press." type="book" year="2009">Losos, 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FCB0FC98FC724216" blockId="11.[803,1419,197,1901]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
Small anoles of MT3 live in the lowlands, and use mostly tree trunks from the understorey to the canopy (
<tableCitation id="C6BA0334A224FFF2FCA7FCD5FC184519" box="[811,909,839,861]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[141,205,992,1011]" captionText="Table 1. Comparisons of Anolis beta diversity amongst ecogeographical regions" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Table S1</tableCitation>
). Whereas 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FB83FCD5FB4F4518" authorityName="Poe, Velasco, Miyata &amp; Williams" authorityYear="2009" box="[1039,1242,839,860]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anchicayae">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FB83FCD5FB4F4518" box="[1039,1242,839,860]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis anchicayae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FB65FCD5FA114518" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1898" box="[1257,1412,839,860]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chloris">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FB65FCD5FA114518" box="[1257,1412,839,860]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis chloris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FCA8FCF4FC29453F" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1868" box="[804,956,870,891]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ortonii">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FCA8FCF4FC29453F" box="[804,956,870,891]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis ortonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FC79FCF4FB37453F" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1898" box="[1013,1186,870,891]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="peraccae">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FC79FCF4FB37453F" box="[1013,1186,870,891]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis peraccae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resemble the trunkcrown ecomorph, 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FC6BFC16FB3845DE" box="[999,1197,900,922]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pentaprion">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FC6BFC16FB3845DE" box="[999,1197,900,922]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis pentaprion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was previously recognized as twig anole (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FB90FC31FB6645FC" author="Irschick DJ &amp; Vitt LJ &amp; Zani P &amp; Losos JB" box="[1052,1267,931,953]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="2191 - 2203" refId="ref10995" refString="Irschick DJ, Vitt LJ, Zani P, Losos JB. 1997. A comparison of evolutionary radiations in mainland and West Indian Anolis lizards. Ecology 78: 2191 - 2203." type="journal article" year="1997">
Irschick 
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FBF6FC36FB3D45FC" box="[1146,1192,931,953]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">et al</emphasis>
., 1997
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FB71FC31FA1545FD" author="Losos JB" box="[1277,1408,931,953]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" refId="ref11304" refString="Losos JB. 2009. Lizards in an evolutionary tree: ecology and adaptive radiation of anoles. Berkeley: University of California Press." type="book" year="2009">Losos, 2009</bibRefCitation>
). For the latter two species, recent ecological data (R. A. Moreno-Arias, unpubl. data) plus their lichenose colour pattern indicate that these species resemble the Caribbean trunk ecomorph more than the trunkcrown ecomorph.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FCB0FBC8FB74436C" blockId="11.[803,1419,197,1901]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
Small and tiny anoles of MT4 are found from midmountain to Paramos regions, and use branches and twigs from the understorey to the canopy (
<tableCitation id="C6BA0334A224FFF2FA94FB0AFAEE42EA" box="[1304,1403,1176,1198]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[141,205,992,1011]" captionText="Table 1. Comparisons of Anolis beta diversity amongst ecogeographical regions" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Table S1</tableCitation>
). This group shows a greater similarity to a Caribbean ecomorph than does any other group. In the same vein as other studies (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FC69FB61FB5F434E" author="Schaad EW &amp; Poe S" box="[997,1226,1267,1290]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="852 - 859" refId="ref12152" refString="Schaad EW, Poe S. 2010. Patterns of ecomorphological convergence among mainland and island Anolis lizards. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 101: 852 - 859." type="journal article" year="2010">Schaad &amp; Poe, 2010</bibRefCitation>
), our results also identified MT4 species as twig anoles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF2FCB0FAA3FC3143BA" blockId="11.[803,1419,197,1901]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
Species of MT1 use mostly trunks and branches of small trees, shrubs, and herbs of the understorey or herbaceous strata, but rarely use the ground (
<tableCitation id="C6BA0334A224FFF2FA91FAFCFAE943C0" box="[1309,1404,1390,1412]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[141,205,992,1011]" captionText="Table 1. Comparisons of Anolis beta diversity amongst ecogeographical regions" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Table S1</tableCitation>
). Only two species (
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FBA9FA1EFB7D43E6" authorityName="Daudin" authorityYear="1802" box="[1061,1256,1420,1442]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="auratus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FBA9FA1EFB7D43E6" box="[1061,1256,1420,1442]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis auratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FAB0FA1EFC234384" authorityName="D'orbigny" authorityYear="1837" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fuscoauratus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FAB0FA1EFC234384" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis fuscoauratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) have been recognized by other authors as grass-bush anoles (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FBA9FA58FA99439B" author="Irschick DJ &amp; Vitt LJ &amp; Zani P &amp; Losos JB" box="[1061,1292,1482,1504]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="2191 - 2203" refId="ref10995" refString="Irschick DJ, Vitt LJ, Zani P, Losos JB. 1997. A comparison of evolutionary radiations in mainland and West Indian Anolis lizards. Ecology 78: 2191 - 2203." type="journal article" year="1997">
Irschick 
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FB07FA58FB2E439B" box="[1163,1211,1482,1503]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">et al</emphasis>
., 1997
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FA96FA58FC0D43BA" author="Schaad EW &amp; Poe S" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="852 - 859" refId="ref12152" refString="Schaad EW, Poe S. 2010. Patterns of ecomorphological convergence among mainland and island Anolis lizards. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 101: 852 - 859." type="journal article" year="2010">Schaad &amp; Poe, 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA224FFF5FCB0F995FED4475C" blockId="11.[803,1419,197,1901]" lastBlockId="12.[166,782,197,1565]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="644" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">
Species of MT2 inhabit the ground, leaf litter, and log falls, and sometimes use shrubs and herbs (
<tableCitation id="C6BA0334A224FFF2FAACF9B7FAE84078" box="[1312,1405,1573,1596]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[141,205,992,1011]" captionText="Table 1. Comparisons of Anolis beta diversity amongst ecogeographical regions" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Table S1</tableCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FCA8F9D6FB80401E" author="Schaad EW &amp; Poe S" box="[804,1045,1604,1626]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="852 - 859" refId="ref12152" refString="Schaad EW, Poe S. 2010. Patterns of ecomorphological convergence among mainland and island Anolis lizards. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 101: 852 - 859." type="journal article" year="2010">Schaad &amp; Poe (2010)</bibRefCitation>
identified 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FB18F9D6FAFC401D" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1898" box="[1172,1385,1604,1625]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="granuliceps">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FB18F9D6FAFC401D" box="[1172,1385,1604,1625]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis granuliceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a member of the grass-bush ecomorph despite it was the species morphologically furthest from members of the grass-bush group. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA224FFF2FB97F932FB6E40F2" author="Irschick DJ &amp; Vitt LJ &amp; Zani P &amp; Losos JB" box="[1051,1275,1696,1718]" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" pagination="2191 - 2203" refId="ref10995" refString="Irschick DJ, Vitt LJ, Zani P, Losos JB. 1997. A comparison of evolutionary radiations in mainland and West Indian Anolis lizards. Ecology 78: 2191 - 2203." type="journal article" year="1997">
Irschick 
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FBF6F932FB3D40F1" box="[1146,1192,1696,1717]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">et al</emphasis>
. (1997)
</bibRefCitation>
showed that 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA224FFF2FCA8F92CFB9D4097" box="[804,1032,1726,1747]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="643" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="trachyderma">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA224FFF2FCA8F92CFB9D4097" box="[804,1032,1726,1747]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="643">Anolis trachyderma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the morphological centroid of the trunk-ground morphotype, but its nearest neighbour was a grass-bush species. Matching a Caribbean ecomorph for the MT2 species is complicated, and requires more quantitative data of their ecology; however, we suggest that species of MT2 correspond to a unique mainland ecomorph owing to their greater preference for the ground compared with the other morphotypes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA223FFF5FF33FEB3FF634794" blockId="12.[166,782,197,1565]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">
MT5 anoles use tree trunks, shrubs, and ground in nearly the same proportions (
<tableCitation id="C6BA0334A223FFF5FDCCFEADFD334711" box="[576,678,319,341]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[141,205,992,1011]" captionText="Table 1. Comparisons of Anolis beta diversity amongst ecogeographical regions" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Table S1</tableCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FD4FFEADFE9F4737" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1864" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scypheus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FD4FFEADFE9F4737" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis scypheus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grouped within the trunk-ground ecomorph (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA223FFF5FF22FEEEFE0147D7" author="Irschick DJ &amp; Vitt LJ &amp; Zani P &amp; Losos JB" box="[174,404,380,403]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" pagination="2191 - 2203" refId="ref10995" refString="Irschick DJ, Vitt LJ, Zani P, Losos JB. 1997. A comparison of evolutionary radiations in mainland and West Indian Anolis lizards. Ecology 78: 2191 - 2203." type="journal article" year="1997">
Irschick 
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FE9FFEEFFED147D5" box="[275,324,380,402]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">et al</emphasis>
., 1997
</bibRefCitation>
), and the ecology of the remaining species suggests that they are also trunk-ground anoles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA223FFF5FF33FE4BFD90453F" blockId="12.[166,782,197,1565]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">
Large anoles of MT9, despite their shared morphological attributes, show disparate microhabitat uses. 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FF2AFD87FEAD446E" authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[166,312,533,554]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fraseri">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FF2AFD87FEAD446E" box="[166,312,533,554]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis fraseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
uses tree trunks in the canopy like species of MT10; 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FE96FDA6FEE8440E" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="1963" box="[282,381,564,586]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mirus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FE96FDA6FEE8440E" box="[282,381,564,586]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">A. mirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to species of MT6 that also use branches in the understorey, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FD37FDC1FC98442C" baseAuthorityName="O'shaughnessy" baseAuthorityYear="1875" box="[699,781,595,616]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="onca">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FD37FDC1FC98442C" box="[699,781,595,616]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">A. onca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a typical anole of xerophytic vegetation near beaches that uses bushes, shrubs, and the ground, similar to species of MT1. It is interesting that MT5 anoles possess the most robust bodies and some authors have observed very aggressive behaviour in 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FDE5FD7EFD404545" authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1859" box="[617,725,748,769]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fraseri">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FDE5FD7EFD404545" box="[617,725,748,769]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">A. fraseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FF2AFC98FE924564" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="1963" box="[166,263,778,800]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mirus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FF2AFC98FE924564" box="[166,263,778,800]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">A. mirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(F. Castro-Herrera &amp; S. Ayala, unpubl. data), which leaves the relationship between body robustness and aggressive behaviour occurring in this clade as an open hypothesis to test.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA223FFF5FF33FC16FD04434E" blockId="12.[166,782,197,1565]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">
Semiaquatic anoles do not constitute a morphologically distinctive group on the basis of the characters used here. Instead, three species (
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FDAAFC50FD2D4593" authorityName="Miyata" authorityYear="1985" box="[550,696,962,983]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lynchi">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FDAAFC50FD2D4593" box="[550,696,962,983]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis lynchi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FD4BFC50FE8E45B1" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1862" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="poecilopus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FD4BFC50FE8E45B1" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis poecilopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FEECFC72FE6F45B1" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="1984" box="[352,506,992,1013]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rivalis">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FEECFC72FE6F45B1" box="[352,506,992,1013]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis rivalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were assigned to MT5 and the other two species (
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FE42FC6DFD054250" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1911" box="[462,656,1023,1044]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FE42FC6DFD054250" box="[462,656,1023,1044]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FD44FC6DFEA64276" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="1984" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maculigula">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FD44FC6DFEA64276" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis maculigula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to MT1 and MT8, respectively. All semiaquatic species use vegetation of herbaceous and understorey strata surrounding streams and pools, but also use other microhabitats. 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FE7AFBEBFD2B42CA" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1911" box="[502,702,1145,1166]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrolepis">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FE7AFBEBFD2B42CA" box="[502,702,1145,1166]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">Anolis macrolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also found on the ground, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FDD9FB0AFC9042E9" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="1984" box="[597,773,1176,1197]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maculigula">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FDD9FB0AFC9042E9" box="[597,773,1176,1197]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">A. maculigula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FF2AFB25FEAC428F" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1862" box="[166,313,1206,1228]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="poecilopus">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FF2AFB25FEAC428F" box="[166,313,1206,1228]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">A. poecilopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D0CA223FFF5FEF6FB25FE77428F" authorityName="Williams" authorityYear="1984" box="[378,482,1206,1228]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rivalis">
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FEF6FB25FE1E4288" box="[378,395,1207,1228]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B94CEA9DA223FFF5FE15FB24FE77428F" box="[409,482,1206,1227]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">rivalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
use rocks and boulders in streams and pools (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA223FFF5FE02FB47FDAB42AE" author="Williams EE" box="[398,574,1237,1259]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" pagination="1 - 22" refId="ref12428" refString="Williams EE. 1984. New or problematic Anolis from Colombia. 3. Two new semiaquatic anoles from Antioquia and Choco, Colombia. Breviora 478: 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="1984">Williams, 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA223FFF5FDC2FB47FD7C42AF" author="Miyata KI" box="[590,745,1237,1259]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" pagination="1 - 13" refId="ref11556" refString="Miyata KI. 1985. A new Anolis of the lionotus group from northwestern Ecuador and southwestern Colombia (Sauria: Iguanidae). Breviora 481: 1 - 13." type="journal article" year="1985">Miyata, 1985</bibRefCitation>
; F. Castro-Herrera &amp; S. Ayala, unpubl. data).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B87368FA223FFF5FF33FA80FE674058" blockId="12.[166,782,197,1565]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">
Therefore, semiaquatic anoles support the idea that the semiaquatic habit can be acquired through a variety of body plans. Another possibility is that other traits not evaluated here, such as tail shape (related to swimming performance), could be a link amongst species exhibiting a semiaquatic ecology, as suggested by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA94B7EA223FFF5FD59FA39FE0543A4" author="Leal M &amp; Knox AK &amp; Losos JB" pageId="12" pageNumber="644" pagination="785 - 791" refId="ref11144" refString="Leal M, Knox AK, Losos JB. 2002. Lack of convergence in aquatic Anolis lizards. Evolution 56: 785 - 791." type="journal article" year="2002">Leal, Knox &amp; Losos (2002)</bibRefCitation>
. Studies on performance and morphology will give some clues to defining semiaquatic anoles as an ecomorph 
<typeStatus id="5483882DA223FFF5FE36F995FE7A4058" box="[442,495,1543,1564]" pageId="12" pageNumber="644">type</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
